  "prompt": "What's the difference between drowning in Salt water and normal water?",
  "response": "There are some key differences between drowning in saltwater and freshwater:\n\nSaltwater Drowning:\n1. More immediate physiological response\n2. Causes rapid dehydration of lung cells\n3. Salt draws water out of bloodstream into lungs\n4. Lung damage occurs faster\n5. Higher risk of electrolyte imbalance\n6. Slightly slower oxygen deprivation\n\nFreshwater Drowning:\n1. Water enters lungs and dilutes blood\n2. Causes lung cells to swell\n3. Reduces surfactant (lung lubricant)\n4. Faster oxygen deprivation\n5. Reduces lung's ability to exchange oxygen\n6. Higher risk of immediate cardiac arrest\n\nBoth types are life-threatening and require immediate medical attention. The underlying mechanism is similar - preventing oxygen from reaching the bloodstream - but the specific cellular processes differ slightly between salt and fresh water.\n\nSurvival chances depend on:\n- Time underwater\n- Water temperature\n- Victim's physical condition\n- Speed of rescue and medical intervention",
